# Event System

The Event System is how different systems communicate without being tightly coupled. One system emits an event, and other systems listen and react.

## Why Events?

### Without Events (Tightly Coupled)

// Bad: CombatSystem directly calls HealthSystem
var health = _entityManager.GetComponent(target);
health.Health -= damage;

// Now CombatSystem depends on HealthSystem
// If HealthSystem changes, CombatSystem might break
// Hard to test CombatSystem in isolation


### With Events (Loosely Coupled)

// Good: CombatSystem emits event
var damageEvent = new DamageEvent(target, damage);
RaiseLocalEvent(target, damageEvent);

// HealthSystem listens for DamageEvent
// CombatSystem doesn't know or care who listens
// Easy to add new listeners without changing CombatSystem


## How Events Work


System A emits:
  |
DamageEvent created
  |
All listeners are called:
  - HealthSystem listens -> Applies damage
  - AudioSystem listens -> Plays hit sound
  - ParticleSystem listens -> Shows blood effect
  - StatusEffectSystem listens -> Applies bleeding
  |
Event processing complete


Each system does its job, independently.

## Creating an Event


// In Content.Shared/_OE14/Events/
public sealed class DamageEvent : EntityEventArgs
{
    public EntityUid Target { get; }
    public int Damage { get; }
    public EntityUid? Source { get; }

    public DamageEvent(EntityUid target, int damage, EntityUid? source = null)
    {
        Target = target;
        Damage = damage;
        Source = source;
    }
}


Events are simple data containers that hold information about what happened.

## Raising (Emitting) an Event


public class CombatSystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly EntityManager _entityManager = default!;

    public void AttackEnemy(EntityUid attacker, EntityUid target, int damage)
    {
        // Calculate actual damage
        int actualDamage = CalculateDamage(attacker, target, damage);

        // Emit event
        var damageEvent = new DamageEvent(target, actualDamage, attacker);
        RaiseLocalEvent(target, damageEvent);

        // Rest of attack logic
    }
}


[mono]RaiseLocalEvent(entity, event)[/mono] tells the framework: "Hey, something happened to this entity!"

## Listening to Events


public class HealthSystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly EntityManager _entityManager = default!;

    // This method is called when DamageEvent is raised
    private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
    {
        // Apply damage
        entity.Comp.Health -= args.Damage;

        // Stop if health went negative
        if (entity.Comp.Health <= 0)
            entity.Comp.Health = 0;
    }
}


The framework automatically calls [mono]OnDamage[/mono] whenever DamageEvent is raised.

## Event Handler Naming Convention

Handler methods follow a pattern:

private void On(, ref )
{
    // Handle the event
}


Examples:
- [mono]OnDamage[/mono] for DamageEvent
- [mono]OnDeath[/mono] for DeathEvent
- [mono]OnSpellCast[/mono] for SpellCastEvent

## Multiple Systems Listening

Multiple systems can listen to the same event:


// In HealthSystem
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    entity.Comp.Health -= args.Damage;
}

// In AudioSystem
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    PlaySound("hit.wav");
}

// In ParticleSystem
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    ShowBloodEffect(entity);
}

// In StatusEffectSystem
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    if (args.Damage > 20)
        ApplyStatusEffect(entity, "Bleeding");
}


When DamageEvent is raised:
1. HealthSystem applies damage
2. AudioSystem plays sound
3. ParticleSystem shows effect
4. StatusEffectSystem applies bleed

All independently!

## Event Propagation

Events propagate through entity hierarchy:


Child entity takes damage
  |
OnDamage called for child
  |
Event bubbles up to parent
  |
OnDamage called for parent
  |
Event continues bubbling


You can stop propagation:

private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    entity.Comp.Health -= args.Damage;
    args.Handled = true;  // <- Stop propagation
}


## Event Performance

Events are very efficient:
- Zero allocation for event handlers (uses method pointers)
- Events processed immediately (no queue)
- Handler lookup is O(1) with caching

Safe to raise hundreds of events per frame!

## Real Example: Combat Flow


// CombatSystem raises event
public void AttackEnemy(EntityUid attacker, EntityUid target)
{
    int baseDamage = 20;
    int actualDamage = CalculateModifiers(attacker, baseDamage);

    var damageEvent = new DamageEvent(target, actualDamage, attacker);
    RaiseLocalEvent(target, damageEvent);
}

// HealthSystem listens
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    entity.Comp.Health -= args.Damage;

    if (entity.Comp.Health <= 0)
    {
        var deathEvent = new DeathEvent(args.Source);
        RaiseLocalEvent(entity, deathEvent);  // Chain events!
    }
}

// DeathSystem listens
private void OnDeath(Entity entity, ref DeathEvent args)
{
    RemoveEntity(entity);
}

// LootSystem listens
private void OnDeath(Entity entity, ref DeathEvent args)
{
    DropLoot(entity);
}

// AudioSystem listens
private void OnDeath(Entity entity, ref DeathEvent args)
{
    PlaySound("death.wav");
}


Single attack triggers multiple reactions through events!

## Filtered Events

Events can be filtered to specific components:


// Only call this if entity has HealthComponent
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    // Only entities with HealthComponent reach here
}

// Only call if entity has ArmorComponent
private void OnDamage(Entity entity, ref DamageEvent args)
{
    // Reduce damage based on armor
    args.Damage *= (1 - entity.Comp.ArmorRating);
}


Framework automatically calls the right handler based on component!

## Directed vs Broadcast Events

### Directed (To One Entity)

RaiseLocalEvent(entity, new DamageEvent(...));  // Only this entity gets it


### Broadcast (To Everyone)

RaiseLocalEvent(new GlobalEventArgs());  // All systems get it


Most events are directed to a specific entity.

## Best Practices

[bold]DO:[/bold]
- Emit events for important changes
- Let multiple systems listen independently
- Name events clearly (DamageEvent, DeathEvent, etc.)
- Keep event data minimal and relevant
- Chain events when needed (death triggers loot drop)

[bold]DON'T:[/bold]
- Create huge event payloads (network them efficiently)
- Have events call back into emitter (circular logic)
- Emit events every frame for continuous data (use components)
- Make systems depend on event order

## Event Examples in OpenEdge

[bold]DamageEvent[/bold] — emitted by CombatSystem, listened by HealthSystem, StatusEffectSystem, AudioSystem

[bold]DeathEvent[/bold] — emitted by HealthSystem, listened by LootSystem, AudioSystem, UISystem

[bold]SpellCastEvent[/bold] — emitted by SpellSystem, listened by ManaSystem, AudioSystem, ParticleSystem

[bold]ItemPickupEvent[/bold] — emitted by InventorySystem, listened by AudioSystem, UISystem

[bold]StatModifierEvent[/bold] — emitted by CharacterStatsSystem, listened by UISystem, ValidationSystem

## Debugging Events

### Problem: Handler not being called
1. Check: Is the handler method named [mono]On[EventName][/mono]?
2. Check: Does it accept [mono]Entity\[/mono] and [mono]ref EventType[/mono]?
3. Check: Is the event actually being raised with [mono]RaiseLocalEvent[/mono]?

### Problem: Event called twice
1. Check: Are multiple systems handling the same event?
2. Check: Is event being raised twice?
3. Check: Is propagation disabled ([mono]args.Handled = true[/mono])?

## Navigation

- Want to communicate between systems? Use events
- Need to prevent cheating? Validate in event handlers
- Want to add a new system? Listen to relevant events
- Debugging a mechanic? Check what events are being raised

## Summary

- [bold]Events[/bold] decouple systems
- [bold]RaiseLocalEvent[/bold] emits an event
- [bold]On[EventName] method[/bold] handles events
- [bold]Multiple listeners[/bold] react independently
- [bold]Very efficient[/bold] even at high frequency

Events are the communication backbone of OpenEdge 14!
